Subject: Bogus ROOT domain server on ARPAnet
Goal-Of-The-Day: An empty Mailbox.
Date: Mon, 08 Jun 87 22:40:46 -0500
From: Paul Richards &lt;richards%shangrila.cs.uiuc.edu@a.cs.uiuc.edu&gt;

Hi Hostmaster...

I'm not sure you're the right group to handle this, but if not, you can point
me in the right direction.

Tonight, we had what I'd call a major failure on the ARPA domain name system.
A system at NORTHWESTERN.ARPA, [10.4.0.94], started advertising itself as a
root domain name server, with the consequences that we stopped being able to
locate any domain names at all.  I called NOC around 11:15pm EST, talked to
a gentleman named Ron, who eventually looped back NORTHWESTERN until he could
talk to their system admin.

The main question now is, what or who is the right organization to contact for
problems of this kind?  NOC wasn't sure what could be done other than cutting
off the host from the net.  Is there an operations center handling domain
servers? 

If we are going to use the domain system for all it's intended uses, it has
to remain up as much as possible.  (and we do use it for the great majority
of our mail and name resolution)  

Thanks for your attention on this.

Paul Richards	University of Illinois at Urbaba-Champaign; Computer Science
		richards@b.cs.uiuc.edu
		+217 333-3536
